no-void.description:
Description

This rule aims to eliminate use ofvoidoperator.

Examples ofincorrectcode for this rule:

/*eslint no-void: "error"*/

void foo
void someFunction();

const foo = void bar();
function baz() {
    return void 0;
}

no-void.option:
This rule has an object option:

- allowAsStatementset totrueallows thevoidoperator to be used as a statement (Defaultfalse).

allowAsStatement

WhenallowAsStatementis set to true, the rule will not error on cases that thevoidoperator is used as a statement, i.e. when itâ€™s not used in an expression position, like in a variable assignment or a function return.

Examples ofincorrectcode for{ "allowAsStatement": true }:

/*eslint no-void: ["error", { "allowAsStatement": true }]*/

const foo = void bar();
function baz() {
    return void 0;
}

Examples ofcorrectcode for{ "allowAsStatement": true }:

/*eslint no-void: ["error", { "allowAsStatement": true }]*/

void foo;
void someFunction();
